comment.editorialComment: Our original forecast for this month was for an overall movement of -1.0% by the end of the month. However, the Black Book movements for the first 10 days of the month are approaching just short of -0.5%. With this in mind, we now forecast that there is likely to be a further overall movement of around -0.5%

This sector like many others is heavily dominated by fleet volume and it will come as no surprise that September is one of the peak months in terms of registrations. However, it is normal for there to be a bit of a delay in the return cars hitting the used market and therefore we expect to see an increase in used volumes during October which in turn is likely to put some pressure on values. This doesnâ€™t mean that the market is likely to go into free-fall but a softening of around -1% - -1.5% should be expected.

In what seems to have been a fairly stable market so far this year, there may be a bit of catching up to do and usually, November is the month when that happens. This is usually driven by a lack of footfall as retail buyers turn their focus towards the end of the year as well as trade buyers taking stock of what they already have and looking forwards to what they might carry into the New Year. That said, there are still open cheque books but the price has to reflect the level of risk and this usually means values are likely to fall.
